32
00:02:14,466 --> 00:02:17,300
This work involved design,
analysis and performance

33
00:02:17,366 --> 00:02:18,400
evaluation.

34
00:02:18,466 --> 00:02:20,699
It's well described in the
book they've written together.

35
00:02:22,000 --> 00:02:25,699
More recently, Joan co-designed
the Keccak cryptographic hash

36
00:02:25,766 --> 00:02:29,500
based on the sponge design which
was selected as a new SHA-3 hash

37
00:02:29,566 --> 00:02:30,266
in 2012.

38
00:02:31,766 --> 00:02:34,566
Joan has had a long
career in industry.

39
00:02:34,633 --> 00:02:38,500
In 2017, he won the Levchin
prize for contributions to

40
00:02:38,566 --> 00:02:39,633
world cryptography.

41
00:02:39,699 --> 00:02:43,000
He is now a Professor of
Symmetric Cryptography at the

42
00:02:43,066 --> 00:02:46,533
Radboud University Nijmegen
in the Netherlands.

43
00:02:46,599 --> 00:02:49,232
Unfortunately, Joan Daemen was
not able to make it to the

44
00:02:49,300 --> 00:02:50,066
conference today.

45
00:02:52,766 --> 00:02:55,433
This year's other winner,
Professor Vincent Rijmen, is

46
